td.paragraph: Reference range: <100
Desirable range <100 mg/dL for primary prevention;
<70 mg/dL for patients with CHD or diabetic patients
with > or = 2 CHD risk factors.
LDL-C is now calculated using the Martin-Hopkins
calculation, which is a validated novel method providing
better accuracy than the Friedewald equation in the
estimation of LDL-C.
Martin SS et al. JAMA. 2013;310(19): 2061-2068
(http://education.QuestDiagnostics.com/faq/FAQ164)
For patients with diabetes plus 1 major ASCVD risk
factor, treating to a non-HDL-C goal of <100 mg/dL
(LDL-C of <70 mg/dL) is considered a therapeutic
option.

Currently, no consensus exists regarding use of

According to American Diabetes Association (ADA)

control in non-pregnant diabetic patients. Different
metrics may apply to specific patient populations.

testing of troponin I at intervals of 2 to 4 hours
for up to 12 to 24 hours is suggested in order to
corroborate a single troponin I result. An elevated
troponin alone is not sufficient to make the
diagnosis of MI.

td.paragraph: This is a 29-year-old male, new patient, with significant past medical history of ulcerative colitis, whom he follows with his gastroenterologist, Dr. Xiao Tan in Boston, Massachusetts, referred by Zocdoc, who presents today for initial cardiovascular consultation with complaints of chest pain. He currently works as a third-grade teacher in Danbury, Connecticut. He has zero children and lives in Poughkeepsie, New York. He establishes PCP with Dr. Andrey Takhtovich at Nuvance in Highland. He is a current THC smoker and a social ETOH user, having about three drinks per week. He has a past surgical history of wisdom tooth removal. He has a past family history of his maternal grandfather having CVA and his maternal uncle having DM, with his mother and father being healthy. He is prescribed mesalamine to be taken as needed; however, he reports he has not taken this medication in over a year. He initially presented himself to the emergency department at Mid-Hudson Regional Hospital on 06/26/2025 with complaints of substernal chest pain. A chest x-ray was completed at that time revealing no pleural effusion, no pneumothorax, with cardiomediastinal silhouette intact and lungs being clear. He was then discharged in stable condition. He was then seen back at the emergency department on 07/22/2025 for left-sided chest pain and tingling, and blurry vision. He was ordered IV Toradol 15 mg that he reports improved his symptoms of blurry vision. A CT head without contrast was completed revealing no significant findings. A CT chest was also completed revealing no acute aortic injury with no acute intrathoracic abnormality. The attending physician also ordered a CT angio head and neck revealing no abnormality. He was discharged in stable condition. He then reports following with his primary care provider whom ordered a brain MRI results at this time are still pending. He then presented himself to the emergency department for a third time with complaints of shortness of breath at rest as well as near-syncope. He was discharged in stable condition. He reports that at the time of his dyspnea, he was eating ice-cream on his couch. His most recent presentation to the emergency department occurred on 07/27/2025, where he experienced significant left-sided chest pain, left-sided arm pain, and weakness, as well as palpitations and muscle spasms. For his palpitations, he was given Toprol in the emergency department which he reports significantly improved these episodes. He describes his muscle spasms occurring at the site of his left nipple, where this feeling beings as an initial twitch and then turns into a more consistent spasm. This feeling also occurs in the umbilical region of his abdomen that is associated with his episodes of chest pain. He was prescribed propranolol 10 mg which he has been taking with no ill side-effects reported. He was then discharged in stable condition. On Tuesday, 08/07/2025, he states to be cooking in his kitchen. He reports that he suddenly "saw stars" and experienced a very sharp left-sided chest pain. He presented himself to the Urgent Care the same day where he was encouraged to follow with cardiology. He also reports that upon self-palpation of his left chest, he experiences slight discomfort. He gives the example of when his girlfriends head was lying on his chest, he felt moderate discomfort. He reports that he did have an ulcerative colitis flare from late June until mid-July. The first onset of his left-sided chest pain occurred over a month ago and has been a dull pain progressing ever since. He denies any full syncopal events.
Echocardiogram: Revealed trace MR with an ejection fraction of 50% to 55%.

Routine lab work was completed today for evaluation for his overall health as well as a cardiac injury panel, lipoprotein A, apolipoprotein B, and D-dimer. We will review the results with him at his next visit. We will also arrange for an EKG at his next visit for further evaluation of his significant chest pain. An echocardiogram was completed today for evaluation of cardiac morphology in the setting of chest pain. Preliminary images reviewed and discussed that revealed trace MR with an ejection fraction of 50% to 55%. We also placed an event monitor on him today for evaluation of possible electrical abnormalities causing these cardiac symptoms. We will seek authorization for ETT for further ischemic evaluation of his significant shortness of breath both upon exertion and at rest given his chest pain. We will seek authorization for carotid doppler for evaluation of possible carotid stenosis causing his episodes of dizziness and lightheadedness. For his extremity numbness and tingling, we will seek authorization for ABI/PVR to evaluate her possible PAD causing these symptoms. All questions and concerns were answered and addressed. A heart-healthy diet and healthy lifestyle was encouraged and endorsed. He is to follow-up on Friday or sooner should symptoms worsen or new symptoms arise. He agrees to the plan of care.

This is a 29-year-old male, new patient, with significant past medical history of ulcerative colitis, who presents today for CV follow-up for persistent chest pain. He continues to complain of left-sided dull chest pain. He does report having intermittent episodes of sharper left-sided chest pain. At his previous visit for evaluation of his chest pain, we arranged for an echocardiogram to be performed. We will review and discuss results at today's visit. We also arranged for routine labs for evaluation of his overall health as well as a cardiac injury panel for evaluation of his cardiovascular health. At his last visit, we also arranged for an event monitor to be placed. He is to return his event monitor at today's visit for his persistent dull left-sided chest pain. He denies any significant changes since he was last seen. He denies any worsening of his symptomatology. He also reports that he has not taken anything for the pain, including anything over the counter. He reports that he does not take any medication for pain management for his chest pain. He also previously had a brain MRI ordered by his primary care provider. At this time, results are still pending. He was encouraged to bring results at his next visit. He also reports a history of twitching of his upper and lower extremities as well as a twitching sensation over his left chest. He was evaluated yesterday at New Vance Neurology with an EMG. At his previous visit, we also arranged for an echocardiogram for evaluation of cardiac morphology in the setting of chest pain as well as shortness of breath. We will review and discuss results at today's visit. He previously complained of episodes of lightheadedness and dizziness with no precipitating factors.
